# Autonomous agent and verification

## Execution

- **Do not ask the user for permission** for routine work: run commands, apply migrations, edit code, call MCP tools (Supabase, Netlify, browser, YCode, etc.), and iterate until the task is done.
- **Only stop to ask** when something is truly blocking and only the user can supply it (e.g. a secret they have never provided, or an irreversible production action they must explicitly confirm).
- **Prefer tools over instructions**: if a terminal command, MCP call, or script can establish facts, use it instead of guessing.

## Ship changes: Git ŌåÆ auto deploy (no manual uploads)

- **Never** use Netlify drag-and-drop, zip upload, **`netlify deploy` from the agentŌĆÖs shell**, or Netlify MCP **`deploy-site`** for routine work. Those are **only** for emergencies or when the user explicitly asks for a one-off CLI upload.
- After edits: **`git add` ŌåÆ `git commit` ŌåÆ `git push`** to GitHub on the branch Netlify (or CI) is configured to build. That is the default way to ship.
- **Admin dashboard** (`admin.masjidweb.com`): repo **`mywebmasteruk/masjidweb`**, Netlify site **`masjidweb-admin-v2`** (`11db9c91-9c73-48d4-a93b-88d37e62e1d8`), base **`admin-dashboard-v2/`**. Netlify is linked to Git ŌĆö **push triggers the build** (production branch is **`mw-admin-dash`** unless changed in Netlify). Optionally, **GitHub Actions** (`.github/workflows/deploy-admin-dashboard.yml`) also deploys when `NETLIFY_AUTH_TOKEN` / `NETLIFY_SITE_ID` secrets exist; either way there is **no manual upload**.
- **Builder (`ycode-masjidweb`):** Prefer **commit + push** on whatever repo/branch that Netlify site has linked. Use MCP **`deploy-site`** only if that site still has no Git link and the user has not migrated it yet.
- After push: **wait** until the new production deploy is **`ready`** (Netlify dashboard or `netlify api listSiteDeploys` for the site), then run **browser verification** below.
- **Never consider a task complete until the push landed, auto deploy succeeded, and browser verification passes.**

## Browser verification (required ŌĆö every change)

After every deploy, **always** verify both the admin dashboard and the builder. This is not optional and is part of the standard workflow.

1. **Admin dashboard** ŌĆö `https://admin.masjidweb.com`
   - Navigate to the page affected by the change (e.g. `/dashboard/updates`, `/dashboard`).
   - `browser_navigate` ŌåÆ wait for async content (10ŌĆō15 s for pages with API calls) ŌåÆ `browser_snapshot`.
   - Confirm: correct page title, no error state, expected content visible.

2. **Builder** ŌĆö `https://masjidemo1.masjidweb.com/ycode`
   - Navigate to the builder or the specific settings page if relevant.
   - `browser_snapshot` and confirm: builder loads, no error page, relevant UI state is correct.

3. **If a change touches shared logic** (e.g. update checks, auth, Supabase queries), verify **both** sites even if only one codebase was edited.

### Verification details

- **Do not use `localhost` / `astro dev` / `next dev` as the primary check.** Always verify on the **real Netlify deployment**.
- Use browser MCP: `browser_navigate` ŌåÆ `browser_lock` ŌåÆ sleep for async ŌåÆ `browser_snapshot` ŌåÆ `browser_unlock`.
- **Local dev** is only for debugging; state explicitly when a check was dev-only vs production.

## Non-UI work

- For **backend-only / SQL-only** tasks, **still run** automated checks: tests, typecheck, or targeted scripts. If the change could affect the live app, spot-check the relevant Netlify route after deploy.

## Concision

- Keep updates to the user factual and short; do not ask whether to proceed on standard steps.
